  "sandhi_rules": [
    {
      "id": "AR_SUN_ASSIMILATION",
      "name": "sun-letter-assimilation",
      "left_context": "l$",
      "right_context": "^[tθdðszʃnrlɫɮtˤdˤsˤðˤ]",
      "transform": "",
      "obligatory": true,
      "notes": "al-shams → ash-shams (l assimilates to following sun letter). The emphatic sun letters (ص ض ط ظ → sˤ dˤ tˤ ðˤ) are listed explicitly for clarity/completeness, though the base coronal codepoints (t d s ð) already present in the class matched these on their leading codepoint before this addition — so their inclusion is not closing a real assimilation gap."
    },
    {
      "id": "AR_HAMZAT_WASL",
      "name": "hamzat-al-wasl",
      "left_context": "[aeiouː]$",
      "right_context": "^[ʔ]",
      "transform": "",
      "obligatory": true,
      "notes": "fi al-bayt → fil-bayt (hamzat al-wasl elision after vowel)"
    },
    {
      "id": "AR_PAUSAL_TANWIN",
      "name": "pausal-tanwin",
      "left_context": "[n]$",
      "right_context": "$",
      "transform": "",
      "obligatory": false,
      "notes": "kitāban → kitābā (tanwin drops in pause)"
    }
  ],
  "notes": "Classical Arabic (العربية الفصحى, al-ʿArabiyya al-fuṣḥā). The variety of the Quran and pre-Islamic poetry (~6th–9th c. CE). All modern Arabic dialects descend from spoken Classical Arabic (not from Modern Standard Arabic / MSA). 28-consonant inventory. KEY CLASSICAL FEATURES: (1) ض /ɮˤ/ — emphatic LATERAL fricative (described by Sibawayhi as a lateral sound; modern dialects shift to /dˤ/ or /zˤ/); (2) ث /θ/ and ذ /ð/ fully preserved as interdentals; (3) ء /ʔ/ always realised (not dropped); (4) ق /q/ always uvular (no urban ʔ variant); (5) all three short vowels (/a i u/) fully pronounced (no deletion); (6) word-final case vowels (iʿrāb) pronounced; (7) diphthongs /aj/ and /aw/ preserved (not monophthongised). Source: Sibawayhi, al-Kitāb (8th c.); Wright (1896); Watson (2002).",
